        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The spectral channel width of 0.23 km/s ensures at least 3-4 channels per line profile. The data analysis primarily relies on the integrated intensity of the lines and thus kinematic information is not essential, and is better obtained using more abundant and brighter species. Furthermore, the emission may be weak, so flux sensitivity is the main criterion.

We have added lines of H2CO and SO in basebands 2 and 3 to facilitate serendipitous detections of these previously sought but undetected species in this source. Both contribute to the science of freezeout and ice chemistry.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The angular resolution is the largest allowed at the selected frequency, and allows us to focus on detecting this previously unobserved molecule in disks. The central evaporation zone of CO ice (30au=0.5'' radius or 1'' diameter, Qi et al. 2013) will also be resolved from the rest of the disk, allowing to probe for possible codesorption of some ices. The largest angular scale was chosen to ensure that as much total flux is captured as possible, since we do not yet know the exact spatial distribution of HCl in a real disk, while the total power array cannot be used with the requested frequency setting.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The RMS sensitivity corresponds to a marginal (2-sigma) detection of emission in the low end of the HCl abundance range of interest, which also gives the number entered in "expected line flux". This ensures that if only upper limits are obtained, they are strong enough to be meaningful for a scientific interpretation. The highest HCl abundances of interest would yield a 48 sigma detection. The bandwidth selected is the minimum possible with a spectral resolution that still marginally resolves the lines and will cover all three hyperfine components of the HCl 1-0 transition (separated by +- a few km/s from the strongest component).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
