    <prp:abstract>We propose a new probe of cometary ice evolution in protoplanetary disks: chlorine. Its chemistry in molecular gas is well known, and the main carrier HCl easily observed. The journey of chlorine from ices in protostellar cores to comets is currently a puzzle. Comets yield upper limits on their HCl to H2O ice ratio of order 0.0001, while protostar studies infer values an order of magnitude higher. It is not known whether the HCl ice evaporated in the protoplanetary disk, or was converted and locked into some unknown ice species. The answer lies in the gas-phase chlorine abundance in disks. We will use ALMA observations of HCl in a young Solar System analog to determine whether chlorine in disks has returned to the gas, as suggested by cometary ices. This study is timely, as the Rosetta spacecraft at comet 67P will soon provide the strongest constraint to date of the HCl to H2O ratio in a comet.</prp:abstract>
